<article>

  <!-- INTRO -->
  <section class="intro">
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>
      Upgrading your laptop’s RAM is one of the easiest ways to improve performance,
      increase multitasking capability, and extend the useful life of your device.
      This guide walks you through the general steps for replacing or installing RAM in most Lenovo laptops.
    </p>

    <p><strong>Your model may vary</strong>, so check your device’s hardware manual if something looks different.</p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <!-- BEFORE YOU BEGIN -->
  <section class="section-block">
    <h1>Before You Begin</h1>

    <div class="two-col">
      <div>
        <h2>Tools Needed</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Small Phillips screwdriver</li>
          <li>Plastic pry tool</li>
          <li>Anti-static wrist strap (recommended)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2>Safety</h2>
        <p>
          Always power down the device, unplug the charger, and disconnect all external accessories.
          If the battery is removable, take it out before starting.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <!-- STEP 1 -->
  <section class="step-title">
    <h1>Step 1 — Power Off and Remove the Bottom Cover</h1>
    <p>Before opening the laptop, make sure it is fully powered down and safe to work on.</p>
  </section>

  <step>
    <img src="/images/remove.svg" alt="Disconnect accessories" />
    <div class="step-content">

      <h3>Prepare the Laptop</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Shut down the laptop completely (avoid Sleep or Hibernate).</li>
        <li>Unplug the power adapter and disconnect all accessories.</li>
        <li>Hold the power button for 5–10 seconds to discharge remaining power.</li>
      </ul>

      <danger>
        Opening the laptop while it still has power can damage internal components.
      </danger>

      <p><strong>If your model has a removable battery:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Slide open the locking latches.</li>
        <li>Remove the battery and set it aside.</li>
      </ul>

      <note>
        Some Lenovo models require disabling the internal battery in BIOS.  
        Look for <strong>"Disable Internal Battery"</strong> under the Power menu.
      </note>

    </div>
  </step>

  <hr />

  <!-- STEP 2 -->
  <step>
    <img src="/images/remove.svg" alt="Removing bottom cover screws" />
    <div class="step-content">

      <h3>Remove the Bottom Cover</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Turn the laptop upside down and place it on a soft, non-conductive surface.</li>
        <li>Locate and remove all screws securing the bottom cover.</li>
        <li>Keep screws organized — lengths may vary by model.</li>
        <li>Insert a plastic pry tool into a corner seam.</li>
        <li>Work around the edges to release the internal clips.</li>
        <li>Lift the cover off and set it aside.</li>
      </ul>

      <danger>
        Avoid using metal tools — they can bend the chassis or scratch the finish.
      </danger>

    </div>
  </step>

</article>

